dership of impresarios, the movie theatre rose up from these attacks to become an important social and cultural centre – one deemed “suitable for women and children.”An innovative examination of moviegoing as a social practice and movie exhibition as a commercial enterprise, Reel Time depicts how the industry shaped the development of the Canadian Prairie West and propelled the region into the modern era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMotion picture theatersxEconomic aspectszPrairie ProvincesxHistory. 0aMotion picture theatersxSocial aspectszPrairie ProvincesxHistory. 0aMotion picturesxEconomic aspectszPrairie ProvincesxHistory. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszPrairie ProvincesxHistory. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aMovies.  aNickeolodeon.  aPrairies.  aTheatres.1 aSeiler, Tamara P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781927356005423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781927356005/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles